history.content: It doesn't really make much sense to take 127 and 16b at the same time as 127 is a successor to 16b. Also, all the stuff in 16b that is useful in 127 is taught at the end of the course. I'm assuming you're not eecs as you aren't looking at taking 16a. If you aren't doing EE, there are plenty of courses you could take that don't require 16b. If you are leaning towards ML and that stuff (since you're thinking 127), maybe do 126 instead this semester. Shouldn't be too bad either, as everything up to the first midterm is mostly review of 70 probability. Other than that your schedule looks good

children.subject: Anon here. I guess I was planning to take 16b just to get it out of the way and not have it take up time when I'm taking other high workload upperdivs. So yeah, I was planning to look over the relevant parts in 16a and 16b to prep for 127 and take 16b since my schedule is going to be the most relaxed next semester. Is the workload considering all these classes doable?
People say to take ee126 instead ee127 since material is more relevant in other ML courses if you are into that. ee127 is also helpful but if you can take one of the two then ee126 is the one to go.

history.content: I took Math 54 (also Data 100) and did pretty well but don't recall a lot of the specifics of SVD, PCA, etc. I realized I should take 16B and get it out of the way while reinforcing the learning in 127 along with 161 (cuz im interested in security). Is the workload for this manageable? I am planning to review lin. alg. over the break as well as learn the circuitry part from 16A for 16B. (also looking for advice on how to review lin. alg. as well as study the circuit parts in 16A over the summer) I will have taken all the other CS lower-divs such as 70 and 61C/61B by the end of this semester.
